</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="302936A1C85753709A8ECD6DFD1E27C2" blockId="5.[160,1156,1321,1728]" lastBlockId="8.[160,1157,142,237]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="5" pageNumber="40">
Length (excluding tail filament) 3007 ± 966 µm (677−3668); width at level of excretory pore 144 ± 29 (76−167); oesophagus length 479 ± 52 (373−531): corpus length 370 ± 32 (306−414); isthmus length 10; bulb length 103 ± 20 (64−124); bulb width 114 ± 22 (74 −142); nerve ring 107 ± 28 (63−130) and excretory pore 168 from anterior end, respectively. Prebulbar vulva near mouth 158 ± 46 (61−206) from anterior end. Amphidelphic reproductive apparatus, vagina gives rise to two uteri. Thick-walled muscular ovijector extending posteriorly to join a valved, thin-walled, dilated vagina (
<figureCitation id="A8AD2A24C857537D9A86CE1FFEC22177" box="[168,265,1599,1624]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1625,1648]" captionTargetBox="[167,1138,146,1591]" captionTargetId="figure-1@4.[163,1153,142,1594]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Skrjabinodon campiaoae sp. nov. (a) Female,total length; (b) female, anterior end; (c) female, en face view; (d) female, posterior end, lateral view; (e) egg; (f) male, total length; (g) male, posterior end, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6456954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6456954/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="40">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(b)). In gravid females, the extent of the uteri cannot be seen; in immature females, one uterus extends anteriorly, the other posteriorly. Anus 231 ± 152 (67−366) anterior of tail filament insertion; tail filament 577 ± 136 (291−731) in length, 18–51 small cuticular spines present (
<figureCitation id="A8AD2A24C857537D9820CE87FDA421EF" box="[526,623,1703,1728]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1153,1176]" captionTargetBox="[169,1141,152,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-157@5.[163,1153,142,1121]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron microscope images of Skrjabinodon campiaoae sp. nov. (a) Male, anterior end view (arrow: lateral ala); (b) detail of anterior end of mouth and amphids (arrows); (c) female posterior end." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6456956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6456956/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="40">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(c) and 
<figureCitation id="A8AD2A24C857537D98E2CE87FCE621EF" box="[716,813,1703,1728]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1510,1533]" captionTargetBox="[167,1149,146,1474]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[163,1153,142,1478]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Skrjabinodon campiaoae sp. nov. Male: (a) whole view, (b) detail of posterior end of papillae (arrows). Female: (c) detail of posterior end of spines in the filament tail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6456958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6456958/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="40">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(c)). Fusiform eggs with both ends rounded, length 114 ± 6 (102−124), width 37 ± 8 (19−49); Eggs in initial cleavage. Eggs with smooth surfaces and numerous inside uterus. As the number of eggs increases, the intestine is not visualised (
<tableCitation id="7D14031AC85A5370985AC8F4FD0227C2" box="[628,713,212,237]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="7.[133,189,607,630]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Table 1. Comparative measurements (in µm, with mean followed by the range) of Neotropical species of the genus Skrjabinodon." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/64E96629C855537F9AABCA7FFA472559" pageId="8" pageNumber="43" tableUuid="64E96629C855537F9AABCA7FFA472559">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
